  void lichen_app_interface_test_fail_next_location_submit(int ret)
  {
      k_mutex_lock(&s_mutex, K_FOREVER);
      s_test_next_location_submit_ret = ret < 0 ? ret : 0;  // ignores positive
      k_mutex_unlock(&s_mutex);
  }

  void lichen_app_interface_test_fail_next_clear_network(int ret)
  {
      k_mutex_lock(&s_mutex, K_FOREVER);
      s_test_next_clear_network_ret = ret < 0 ? ret : 0;  // ignores positive
      k_mutex_unlock(&s_mutex);
  }

These test helper functions silently convert positive error codes to 0. While positive values are not standard POSIX errors, some systems use positive values for specific conditions.

If a test accidentally passes a positive value:
- Expected: function returns that value for test verification
- Actual: function returns 0 (success), causing incorrect test behavior

The silent normalization makes debugging test failures harder. Either:
1. Accept all non-zero values as errors
2. Assert/log when a positive value is passed
